    ans ^= x
print(ans)

ğŸ”¹ SHIFT OPERATORS â€” SHORT NOTES

There are 2 types:
1ï¸âƒ£ Left Shift <<
2ï¸âƒ£ Right Shift >>

1ï¸âƒ£ LEFT SHIFT (<<)
ğŸ‘‰ What it does

Shifts bits to the LEFT

Adds 0 at the right end

Multiplies the number by 2

ğŸ”¹ Rule (IMPORTANT â­)
n << k = n Ã— (2^k)

ğŸ”¹ Example 1
5 << 1

here  n = 5 , k= 1 
2 * 1 = 2 
now 5 * 2 = 10

Binary:

5 = 101
â†’ 1010


Decimal:

1010 = 10


âœ… Result:

5 << 1 = 10

ğŸ”¹ Example 2
6 << 2


Binary:

6 = 110
â†’ 11000


Decimal:

11000 = 24


âœ… Result:

6 << 2 = 24

ğŸ”¹ When to use <<

Fast multiplication

n * 2 â†’ n << 1

n * 4 â†’ n << 2

ğŸ”¹ WHERE TO USE LEFT SHIFT (<<)
1ï¸âƒ£ When multiplying by power of 2

Use left shift when multiplication is:

Ã—2, Ã—4, Ã—8, Ã—16, ...

Example:
n = 5
n << 1   # 5 Ã— 2 = 10
n << 2   # 5 Ã— 4 = 20
n << 3   # 5 Ã— 8 = 40


ğŸ‘‰ Used when * is not allowed.

ğŸ”¹ RIGHT SHIFT (>>)
1ï¸âƒ£ What is Right Shift?

ğŸ‘‰ Moves binary bits to the RIGHT
ğŸ‘‰ Removes the last bit
ğŸ‘‰ Divides the number by 2 (integer division)

2ï¸âƒ£ Example (VERY CLEAR)
Example 1
